The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                                                        Lalit Modi lawyer hits out at BCCI
    New Delhi: Former Indian Premier League chairman Lalit Modi rsquo;s counsel claimed that the disciplinary committee formed to probe alleged financial irregularities by his client in running the T20 league has no mandate of BCCI general body and the hearings before the panel should be stopped. Modi rsquo;s lawyer Mehmood Abdi said that the BCCI has done a ldquo;hit wicket rdquo; as it has forgotten to re-constitute the Disciplinary Committee for the year 2010-2011, at its AGM in September.   Pacer hunt
    Kalyani: Former India left-arm pacer Karsan Ghavri said the BCCI has developed a good programme for budding pacers in the country. Ghavri, who was here to spot pace bowlers for the programme, said he was visiting various places to hunt prospective talents. The former left-arm fast bowler said he has so far spotted about 11 pacers from various states. 
    CU in semis
    Calcutta: Calcutta University made it to the semifinals of the Ajoy Ghosh Memorial Trophy cricket tournament, beating Barasat University by eight wickets in the final league match of the Pool 1 in Shantiniketan on Monday.   5-a-side meet
    Calcutta: Bharat Petroleum beat United Conveyor 4-3 (via tie-breaker) in the Calcutta Rangers Club organised five-a-side mercantile meet on Monday. In the other matches, HT Media beat Andrew Yule 3-0, HSBC got the better of Andrew Yule 2-0. Genpact defeated BOC 7-6 (via tie-breaker). 
    Hot debate
    London: Fifa executive Mohamed Bin Hammam has hit back at suggestions by American counterpart Chuck Blazer that Qatar is too hot to host the 2022 World Cup. Bin Hammam responded on his website, claiming that high temperatures are also an issue in the United States. 
    More qualifiers
    Calcutta: The West Bengal Billiards Association will have three qualifying championships before the nationals this year, said West Bengal Billiards Association secretary Debasish Mukhopadhyay on Monday. In the earlier system, only one qualifier was held before the nationals.   Seeds advance
    Calcutta: The seeded players had a good day in the BTA-AITA Talent Series Tennis Tournament, on Monday. In the U-16 boys rsquo; singles first round, seventh seed Ankit Rao beat Akshat Agarwal 7-6, 6-2, while eighth-seed Zaid Ali Akhtar defeated Nitin Kumar Sinha 6-2, 6-1.   Dope case
    Bhubaneswar: Oriya athlete Renubala Mahanta who had tested positive in a dope test conducted by the International Association of Athletics Federation (IAAF) has been handed a two-year ban sentence by the Athletics Federation of India (AFI). 
                                                                                                                                                    
